        LINKEDINCOMMENTEMAILMORESAN FRANCISCO — Salesforce.com has named Tony Prophet as its first chief equality officer to focus on initiatives to bring greater diversity to the business software company.Prophet, a former Microsoft and Hewlett-Packard executive, will report directly to Salesforce chief executive office Marc Benioff.The high-profile appointment reflects the growing emphasis Silicon Valley's technology companies are placing on addressing the lopsided demographics of the industry. Prophet —who sits on the board of Gannett, the parent company of USA TODAY — most recently served as Microsoft's corporate vice president of education marketing.So excited to join the #SalesforceOhana as it does great things in the community and the world! https://t.co/Vwb2ty6Ue7— Tony Prophet (@tony_prophet) September 15, 2016"I always walk into headquarters of companies all over the world and I always look at their values. Everyone knows at Ford that quality is job one. At Salesforce, equality is job one," Benioff told USA TODAY. "That's why you need a senior executive running this mission."Prophet, a prominent African-American tech executive, was co-executive sponsor of Blacks at Microsoft and founding executive of BlackLight, an organization for black marketers at Microsoft."Marc has firmly planted a flag that a corporation can be a force for good in society. And now he's extending that by creating this smart platform for driving not just inclusion and diversity but driving equality," Prophet told USA TODAY.Prophet pledged that racial diversity would be a "heightened priority" at Salesforce.com, which came under fire last year from people of color for focusing diversity efforts on closing the gender gap.USA TODAYSalesforce's Benioff calls for racial equality in techEarlier this week, Benioff called on the tech industry to strive for greater racial equality."In the tech industry we especially have not done well on racial diversity," Benioff said. "I really believe a big reason for that is we haven't focused on it."Rev. Jesse Jackson, who has pressed the tech industry to hire more women and underrepresented minorities, said he was pleased that Salesforce had appointed Prophet."Salesforce is making a deep dive into racial equality," Jackson said.Benioff is a nationally known philanthropist credited with kicking off a new era of corporate social activism among leading chief executives, particularly on gay rights. Benioff says "the  business of business is to improve the state of the world." Now he's turning that activism inwards, appointing Prophet to spearhead efforts to make Salesforce more representative of society at large."A company like Salesforce has to be fighting for more equality at every level and for every person," Benioff said. "The work of diversity is a constant struggle and it requires somebody senior dedicated to this, not just somebody who is kind of functional in the HR organization, but really somebody who is going to work directly for the CEO because these are big, difficult issues that today are paramount to the overall success of the company and the world."USA TODAYBenioff's new philanthropic mission: the oceansClosing the gender and racial gap as they compete in an increasingly global marketplace has become a pressing challenge for tech companies, especially in Silicon Valley. Salesforce.com suffers from the same lack of diversity as other major tech companies. At Salesforce, seven out of 10 employees and eight out of 10 senior leaders around the globe are men. In the U.S., 2% of Salesforce employees are African American and 4% are Hispanic.Q&A with Tony ProphetProphet spoke with USA TODAY about his new role as chief equality officer. The interview has been edited and condensed.On why he took the jobI have been watching Marc and just following the amazing things he has done in the world of philanthropy and obviously watching the business accomplishments. And then when Marc really started putting an emphasis on LGBTQ issues, I really started paying attention to the impact he was having.This spring a mutual acquaintance of ours died, Bill Campbell. I was just thinking about icons and how you never get a chance to tell someone how much of an impact they've had and what a role model they've been. And so I just sat down and just wrote Marc a note and I said: Marc, tough week. Bill died. You will never know the impact you are having on tens millions of people. Let me tell you one: That's my son. My son is LGBTQ transgender. You are opening doors for my son who's this year going to college and as a transgender person had to stand up on the dorm floor and had to tell everyone on the floor: I need those bathrooms to change because I don't feel comfortable using either one of them. You opened those doors for my son. That really accelerated the dialogue for Marc and I. He was moved by this. From that point that conversation was like a snowball. And here I am.On why Salesforce has a chief equality officer I see a natural progression from diversity to inclusion to equality. Diversity is a given, that we are driving for that. Inclusion, certainly. But to drive for equality — equal rights, equal opportunity, equal advancement, equal pay — is the ultimate goal. I think the title signals the strategy and the intent for what we are working to drive and create at Salesforce and foster around the world.On the challenges head for the tech industryWhen you look across the tech industry, for some demographics we have relatively low representations. That's the initial challenge. I am confident we will break through that challenge and you are seeing great progress on some dimensions and work to do on others. But I think the next challenges will be around creating inclusive dialogues, inclusive environments where all opinions are weighed and matter around the table.One of the great things about Salesforce is it's a very dynamic company that's shown its agility when it sets its mind and its resources against an issue, problem or challenge and really quickly is able to rise to the challenge.On Salesforce making racial diversity a priorityIt has certainly been a priority in the past and I would say it's going to be a heightened priority. Of all the dimensions, it's certainly one that Marc and I have talked about, as well as gender as well as LGBTQ issues. So I think you will see a heightened focus on it. I think the numbers are comparable across the industry so there is a tremendous amount of work to be done across the industry.Follow USA TODAY senior technology writer Jessica Guynn @jguynn
            
